To consolidate Hong Kong's status as Asia's fintech hub, the HKMA continues to implement measures to promote the development and application of technology in the banking and payments sectors. Key achievements during the year include:
- Promoting broader adoption of the Fast Payment System ("FPS");
- Encouraging the banking sector to implement open application programming interfaces (open APIs);
- Connecting the Trade Finance Link with the People's Bank of China's (PBOC) trade finance blockchain platform to promote digitalization of trade financing;
- Researching the application of central bank digital currencies (CBDCs) in cross-border payments;
- Exploring the technological feasibility of the Commercial Data Interchange (CDI) and researching alternative credit scoring models to help small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) obtain financing;
- Publishing a two-year plan aimed at developing a more robust and diverse regtech ecosystem, further advancing the application of regtech;
- Enhancing talent cultivation; and
- Advancing cross-border fintech collaboration.

The Exchange Fund Advisory Committee (EFAC) has set the following investment objectives for the Exchange Fund:
(a) To preserve capital;
(b) To ensure that the entire monetary base is fully supported at all times by highly liquid US dollar assets;
(c) To ensure sufficient liquidity to maintain monetary and financial stability; and
(d) To seek investment returns as much as possible within the framework of the above (a) to (c), in order to safeguard the long-term purchasing power of the fund.

During the audit, I will apply professional judgment and maintain professional skepticism. I will also:
- Identify and assess the risks of material misstatement due to fraud or error; design and perform audit procedures to address these risks; and obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence to support my opinion. Because fraud may involve collusion, forgery, intentional omission, false representation, or override of internal control, the risk of not detecting material misstatements resulting from fraud is higher than the risk of not detecting those resulting from error;
- Understand the internal control relevant to the audit to design appropriate audit procedures. However, this does not constitute an opinion on the effectiveness of the Group's internal control;
- Evaluate whether the accounting policies adopted by the Monetary Authority are appropriate, and whether the accounting estimates and related disclosures made are reasonable;
- Determine whether the use of going concern as the basis of accounting by the Monetary Authority is appropriate, and based on the audit evidence obtained, determine whether there are material uncertainties related to events or circumstances that could raise significant doubt about the Group's ability to continue as a going concern. If I conclude that there are material uncertainties, it is necessary to draw the attention of users to the relevant disclosures in the financial statements. If the relevant disclosures are insufficient, I must issue an auditor's report with a qualified opinion. My conclusions are based on the audit evidence obtained up to the date of this auditor's report. However, future events or circumstances may cause the Group to be unable to continue as a going concern;
- Evaluate the overall presentation, structure, and content of the financial statements, including disclosure information, and whether the financial statements fairly reflect the transactions and events; and
- Obtain sufficient and appropriate audit evidence regarding the financial information of entities or business activities within the Group to form an opinion on the financial statements. I am responsible for directing, supervising, and performing the audit of the Group. I bear full responsibility for my audit opinion.

The basis of preparation of these financial statements is on the cost basis, except for the following assets and liabilities measured at fair value:
- Derivative financial instruments (Note 2.6);
- Financial assets and financial liabilities measured at fair value through profit or loss (Note 2.6);
- Financial assets measured at fair value through other comprehensive income (Note 2.6);
- Gold (Note 2.10); and
- Investment properties (Note 2.11).
